WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.250
Unconfined drawdown can pass through aquifer-storage, gravity-drainage, and combined-release regimes.

2
00:00:06.250 --> 00:00:12.500
Capillary force retains pore water above the falling water table, so drainage is not instantaneous.

3
00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:18.750
Assuming instantaneous drainage can distort the specific yield inferred from a pumping test.

4
00:00:18.750 --> 00:00:25.100
The analysis begins with axisymmetric radial-vertical flow in a homogeneous anisotropic aquifer.

5
00:00:25.100 --> 00:00:31.350
The pumping rate is partitioned between aquifer inflow and water released from casing storage.

6
00:00:31.350 --> 00:00:37.700
Equation 7b assigns separate response times to vertical flux and drawdown at the free surface.

7
00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:43.950
The two time shifts are represented by a first-order Taylor expansion.

8
00:00:43.950 --> 00:00:50.300
Substitution into free-surface mass balance gives Equation 9, which returns to Neuman when both lag times vanish.

9
00:00:50.300 --> 00:00:56.550
Dimensionless variables retain aquifer anisotropy, well geometry, and both lag parameters.

10
00:00:56.550 --> 00:01:02.800
The Laplace transform moves the time derivatives into the transform parameter.

11
00:01:02.800 --> 00:01:09.050
The Weber transform resolves the finite-radius radial boundary.

12
00:01:09.050 --> 00:01:15.300
Inverse Weber integration restores radial position in the Laplace domain.

13
00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:21.650
Crump inversion returns the transient drawdown hydrograph in physical time.

14
00:01:21.650 --> 00:01:28.000
The reported sensitivity analysis ranks the drawdown lag above the flux lag.

15
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:34.850
Cape Cod fits give specific-yield estimates of 0.20, 0.16, 0.18, and 0.18.

16
00:01:34.850 --> 00:01:41.600
Borden fits give 0.12, 0.20, 0.11, and 0.17, compared with the cited laboratory value of 0.30.

17
00:01:41.600 --> 00:01:48.450
At Saint Pardon, the fitted lag pair changes between observation distances of 10 and 30 metres.

18
00:01:48.450 --> 00:01:55.200
Across three field sites, the fitted lag times remain test- and site-conditioned rather than universal constants.
